    },
    {
        "content": "<p>which of course is not the first thing a normal maths student would do</p>",
        "id": 525521581,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750772389
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"816344\">@Aaron Liu</span> I understand how your solution works. What I don't understand - and this seems to generally be the case with me - is how to figure out which is the first step of the proof eg. <code>(y - 2) * (x + 5 - (x + 3)) / 2 + 2</code></p>",
        "id": 525537353,
        "sender_full_name": "Răzvan Flavius Panda",
        "timestamp": 1750776836
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There has to be some algorithm / heuristic to determine which is the first step but I do not know what it is.</p>",
        "id": 525537583,
        "sender_full_name": "Răzvan Flavius Panda",
        "timestamp": 1750776899
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Rest of the calculations going from the first step are obvious in comparison. While first step is a mystery.</p>",
        "id": 525537778,
        "sender_full_name": "Răzvan Flavius Panda",
        "timestamp": 1750776949
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>side question... Is teaching people to prove this using only calc useful? My natural pen and paper proof for this looks nothing like calc</p>",
        "id": 525537921,
        "sender_full_name": "Weiyi Wang",
        "timestamp": 1750776990
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"374664\">@Răzvan Flavius Panda</span> yeah it's not very useful; but it comes from chaining the paper proof together into one big block</p>",
        "id": 525538161,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777066
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and working backwards from the last line of the paper proof</p>",
        "id": 525538186,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777075
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110064\">@Kenny Lau</span> so you figure out first step by working backwards from the last line of the paper proof? is that always the algorithm?</p>",
        "id": 525538423,
        "sender_full_name": "Răzvan Flavius Panda",
        "timestamp": 1750777150
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yes</p>",
        "id": 525538515,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777180
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's now how I did it but I guess it works too</p>",
        "id": 525538760,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1750777231
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That leads to other questions, like how do I tell I need to do in <code>- 0 / 2</code> in <code>2 - 0 / 2</code> ?</p>",
        "id": 525538931,
        "sender_full_name": "Răzvan Flavius Panda",
        "timestamp": 1750777287
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"816344\">@Aaron Liu</span> how did you do it? do you have an algorithm?</p>",
        "id": 525538987,
        "sender_full_name": "Răzvan Flavius Panda",
        "timestamp": 1750777309
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>that's the result after writing with <code>h2</code></p>",
        "id": 525539105,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777337
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110064\">@Kenny Lau</span> Yes, but I am reasoning backwards from <code>2</code>. How can I tell I need <code>- 0  / 2</code> next?</p>",
        "id": 525539269,
        "sender_full_name": "Răzvan Flavius Panda",
        "timestamp": 1750777390
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so, let's take 2x+3=5 for an example, how do you solve it on paper?</p>\n<ol>\n<li>2x+3=5</li>\n<li>2x=2</li>\n<li>x=1</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Now, you can think about what you actually did on each step</p>",
        "id": 525539318,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777406
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>from 1. to 2., you subtracted 3 from both sides; from 2. to 3., you divided both sides by 2</p>",
        "id": 525539364,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777423
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what does it mean that you divided both sides by 2? that means 2x divided by 2 is the new LHS x, and 2 divided by 2 is the new RHS 1</p>",
        "id": 525539442,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777445
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so chaining these equalities together, you get x = 2x/2 = 2/2 = 1</p>",
        "id": 525539495,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777458
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>do you understand this?</p>",
        "id": 525539513,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777463
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So first I was thinking that I need to get rid of the <code>y</code>, and the only way to do that is to rewrite using <code>h2</code>. But to rewrite with <code>h2</code> I need <code>y</code> to be multiplied by <code>x</code>. So I see from <code>h1</code> that <code>x = 2</code> need <code>-1/2</code> copies of <code>h2</code> to rewrite with. Then I used <code>h1</code> to spawn in the <code>x</code> and then <code>h2</code> to eliminate the <code>y</code>.</p>",
        "id": 525539554,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1750777475
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/0xGtsHMUAlKIJxIcXMp8sIuI/convert-step.png\">convert-step.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/0xGtsHMUAlKIJxIcXMp8sIuI/convert-step.png\" title=\"convert-step.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"739x262\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/0xGtsHMUAlKIJxIcXMp8sIuI/convert-step.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 525539748,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777543
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>in picture:</p>",
        "id": 525539763,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777550
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110064\">Kenny Lau</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/calc.20xy/near/525539513\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>do you understand this?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I understood the above part. Not the <code>x = 2x/2 = 2/2 = 1</code> Even though I can see why that is true.</p>",
        "id": 525539806,
        "sender_full_name": "Răzvan Flavius Panda",
        "timestamp": 1750777562
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>does the picture help you?</p>",
        "id": 525539858,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777573
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what do you mean when you \"divide both sides by 2\"? it means that you start with 2x=2, and then you divide both sides by two to get 2x/2 = 2/2</p>",
        "id": 525540006,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777610
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and then you simplified both sides to obtain x = 1</p>",
        "id": 525540057,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777617
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>by this, you mean that the LHS 2x/2 simplifies to x, and the RHS 2/2 simplifies to 1</p>",
        "id": 525540116,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777630
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and by \"simplify to\", you mean equal!</p>",
        "id": 525540135,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777635
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so you started from 2x=2, then you divided both sides by two to get 2x/2 = 2/2, and then you used more equalities to obtain x = 2x/2 = 2/2 = 1</p>",
        "id": 525540218,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777661
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok, I understand. But not how this relates to our problem.</p>",
        "id": 525540223,
        "sender_full_name": "Răzvan Flavius Panda",
        "timestamp": 1750777663
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm showing you how to convert from a pen-and-paper proof involving \"manipulation of given equalities\" to a big chain proof</p>",
        "id": 525540316,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777692
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if you understand this simpler case, the more complicated case is just a variation</p>",
        "id": 525540400,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1750777716
